In general, I agree with Karl.  To some extent, though, mixing UUCP and
the Internet is like "crossing the streams" in Ghostbusters.  It's the
old confusion between addresses and routes.

However convenient it may be in some ways, I would contend that using a
fully qualified domain name as a UUCP node name is dangerous.  Despite
the efforts of the mapping project, UUCP node names are relative, and
domain names are absolute, and the two don't mix very well.

The easy suggestion would be to expect hosts that MX for UUCP sites (that
they are not directly connected to) to use strict UUCP paths in order to
route the mail.  This can be done through uunet, for example, since it
has separate names: UUNET.UU.NET for a domain address, and simply "uunet"
for UUCP.

The problem with this is that it's icky :-).  I'm a believer in "one host,
one name," as seem to be lots of people at universities (in particular), who
are ironically the people who are most likely to be willing to MX for
random friends.

Grumble.

Me, I'd say drop UUCP-style addressing altogether, and smash UUCP into a
simple transport layer, but I seem to be in the minority so far.

--
Amanda Walker  &lt;amanda@intercon.uu.net&gt;
